         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">28/8/89 ¶  ¶ From the enclosed telegram ¶  you will perceive, dear Mr Dyer, that an effort is made, to get Verticordia oculata and V. grandis into the conservatories of Kew. If I succeed in this, I sh...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">89.08.28</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Thiselton-Dyer</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1882-90, ff. 288-90.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">28/8/89<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Date stamped</seg>: Royal Gardens Kew 7. Oct. 89; <seg style="font-style: italic; ">annotated, in ink by W. Watson</seg>: <seg style="">570/1899 </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">(i.e. entry number 570 in the Kew Inwards book 1888-1892)</seg>
                     <seg style=""> </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">and in lead pencil by Thiselton-Dyer</seg>
                     <seg style="">: <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>And 7.12.89 <seg style="font-style: italic; ">[letter not found]</seg>.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>From the enclosed telegram<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M. Brown to M, 24 August 1889.</p>
               </note> you will perceive, dear Mr Dyer, that an effort is made, to get <name key="Verticordia%20oculata">Verticordia oculata</name> and V. grandis into the conservatories of Kew. If I succeed in this, I shall regard it as the greatest triumph gained by me in <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">ornamental</hi>
               </seg> culture!<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The entry book records that the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Verticordia</seg> sp. in the box of sand was apparently dead.</p>
               </note> It is not an exaggeration to say, that I have written at least one hundred letters to W.A. purposely during the last thirty years, to accomplish this!<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No such letters have been found.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> — The sandplain south of the Geraldine-mine<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Lead mine, about 120 km north of Geraldton, WA. </p>
               </note> is not easily reached, and when I was there myself in November 1877, the heat was already so scortching, that it was hopeless to carry living plants for a long distance on a packhorse. Seeds were procured over and over again, but these kinds of myrtaceous plants somehow are obstinate in yielding seedlings. I have telegraphed to the Resident Magistrate of K.G. Sound,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>King George Sound, WA; telegram not found.</p>
               </note> to see the case with plants kindly on board of the English Mail-Steamer, and to ask the Captain, to be so friendly, as to take the plants <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>under his special care. You might give the man a trifle, who will water and shade the plants during the voyage, and who will bring them to Kew,<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>bring them to Kew <seg style="font-style: italic; ">is underlined in blue pencil</seg>.</p>
               </note> should they not have perished on the way. In the latter case, we must renew the experiment in the next cool season. I expect cuttings of these rare and unsurpassingly beautiful Verticordias and might try, to get some across to you wrapped up in moist moss and tin-sheet. Look at your specimens in the Kew Herbarium! If once you have the plants, they could be multiplied from cuttings with bottom-warmth under a bell-glass.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">There is a vertical blue line after</seg> glass.</p>
               </note> I shall send you now ferns from the Louisiades,<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Archipelago S. E. of Papua New Guinea.</p>
               </note> also a Schoenus<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <name key="Schoenus%20">Schoenus </name>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">is underlined in blue pencil and</seg> S. calostachyus, Benth<seg style="font-style: italic; ">. is interlined in red ink</seg>.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Described in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7, p. 368 as a recombination of a species described in R. Brown (1810), p. 233 under<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Chaetospora</seg>, a recombination that had already been made in 1811 by Poiret in Lamarck (1783-1817), supplement 2, p. 251.</p>
               </note> from there, which must be kept in that genus, though the pistil is somewhat articulated. I refrain from describing it here, as it may be the Malaian<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Malayan?</p>
               </note> species, noted in the "gen. pl."<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83), vol. 3, pp 1062-3.</p>
               </note> If however new, it might receive Sir Will MacGregors name from Mr Clarke and myself.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Always regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Perhaps after all the people did not get hold of the right kinds of Verticordia I like to keep the experiment in my own hands.<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Paragraph written in margin of f. 288.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>These very local Verticordias will be among the plants, which by sheep-depasturing will soon be swept out of existence.<note xml:id="ftn14" type="footnote" n="14">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Paragraph written in the centre margin of f. 290.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Schoenus%20">Schoenus </name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Verticordia%20grandis">Verticordia grandis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Verticordia%20oculata">Verticordia oculata</name>
            </p>
         </div>
